ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Text description of any abnormal findings. If the examination was completed and there were no abnormal findings, the value should be NORMAL. If the examination was not performed on a particular body system, or at the subject level, then the value should be null, and NOT DONE should appear in PESTAT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for PEORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PESTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: If there are findings for a body system, then either the dictionary preferred term (if findings are coded using a dictionary) or PEORRES (if findings are not coded) should appear here. If PEORRES is null, PESTRESC should be null

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PESTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate exam not done. Should be null if a result exists in PEORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why an examination was not performed or why a body system was not examined. Example: SUBJECT REFUSED. Used in conjunction with STAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PELOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Can be used to specify where a physical exam finding occurred. Example: LEFT ARM for skin rash.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of the test or examination. Examples: XRAY, MRI.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Should be null for records that contain collected or derived data. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, VENDOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of physical exam, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique subject identifier within the submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain to support relationships within the domain and between domains.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the pharmacokinetic parameter. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in PPTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST"). PPTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: AUC, TMAX, CMAX.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the pharmacokinetic parameter. The value in PPTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: AUC, Tmax, Cmax.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a Category of related records. For PP, this should be the name of the analyte in PCTEST whose profile the parameter is associated with.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Categorization of the model type used to calculate the PK parameters. Examples include COMPARTMENTAL, NON-COMPARTMENTAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Result or Finding in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for PPORRES. Example: ng/L.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from PPORRES in a standard format or standard units. PPSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in PPSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from PPSTRESC. PPSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for PPSTRESC and PPSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate that a parameter was not calculated. Should be null if a result exists in PPORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a parameter was not calculated, such as INSUFFICIENT DATA. Used in conjunction with PPSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSPEC
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. If multiple specimen types are used for a calculation (e.g., serum and urine for renal clearance), then this field should be left blank. Examples: SERUM, PLASMA, URINE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Nominal date/time of parameter calculations.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPRFTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of the reference time point from the PC records used to calculate a parameter record. The values in PPRFTDTC should be the same as that in PCRFTDTC for related records.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor‘s operational database. Example: Question number on a questionnaire.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Topic variable for QS. Short name for the value in QSTEST, which can be used as a column name when converting the dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. The value in QSTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g."1TEST"). QSTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: COG01, GH1, PF1.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the question or group of questions used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in QSTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Example: In General, How is Your Health?

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a Category of related records that will be meaningful to the Reviewer. Examples: HAMILTON DEPRESSION SCALE, SF36, ADAS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further Categorization of the questions within the Category. Examples: MENTAL HEALTH DOMAIN, DEPRESSION DOMAIN, WORD RECALL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Finding as originally received or collected (e.g. RARELY, SOMETIMES). When sponsors apply codelist to indicate the code values are statistically meaningful standardized scores, which are defined by sponsors or by valid methodologies such as SF36 questionnaires, QSORRES will contain the decode format, and QSSTRESC and QSSTRESN may contain the standardized code values or scores.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for QSORRES, such as minutes or seconds or the units associated with a visual analog scale.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the finding for all questions or sub-scores, copied or derived from QSORRES in a standard format or standard units. QSSTRESC should store all findings in character format; if findings are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in QSSTRESN. If question scores are derived from the Original finding, then the standard format is the score. Examples: 0, 1. When sponsors apply codelist to indicate the code values are statistically meaningful standardized scores, which are defined by sponsors or by valid methodologies such as SF36 questionnaires, QSORRES will contain the decode format, and QSSTRESC and QSSTRESN may contain the standardized code values or scores.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSSTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from QSSTRESC. QSSTRESN should store all numeric results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for QSSTRESC or QSSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a questionnaire or response to a questionnaire was not done. Should be null if a result exists in QSORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a question was not answered. Used in conjunction with QSSTAT when value is NOT DONE. Example: SUBJECT REFUSED.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSBLFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSDRVFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records or questionnaire sub-scores that do not come from the CRF are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If QSDRVFL=Y, then QSORRES may be null with QSSTRESC and (if numeric) QSSTRESN having the derived value.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date of questionnaire.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of finding collection, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Text Description of time when questionnaire should be administered. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See QSTPTNUM and QSTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSTPTNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Numerical version of QSTPT to aid in sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSELTM
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned Elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (QSTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration. Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by QSTPTREF, or "PT8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by QSTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSTPTREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by QSELTM, QSTPTNUM, and QSTPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSRFTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of the reference time point, LBTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSEVLINT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Evaluation Interval associated with a QSTEST question represented in ISO 8601 character format. Example: "-P2Y" to represent an interval of 2 years in the question "Have you experienced any episodes in the past 2 years?"

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external ECG identifier. Example: UUID.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number from the ECG page.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Description: ECG Test or Examination Short Name
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in EGTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in EGTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST"). EGTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples :PRMEAN, QTMEAN

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in EGTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Summary (Mean) PR Duration, Summary (Mean) QT Duration

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to categorize ECG observations across subjects. Examples: MEASUREMENT, FINDING, INTERVAL

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further Categorization of the ECG.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGPOS
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Position of the subject during a measurement or examination. Examples: SUPINE, STANDING, SITTING.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Result or Finding in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the ECG measurement or finding as originally received or collected. Examples of expected values are 62 or 0.151 when the result is an interval or measurement, or "ATRIAL FIBRILLATION" or "QT PROLONGATION" when the result is a finding.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for EGORRES. Examples: sec or msec.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from EGORRES in a standard format or standard units. EGSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in EGSTRESN. For example, if a test has results of "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in EGORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in EGSTRESC as "NEGATIVE". For other examples, see general assumptions. Additional examples of result data: SINUS BRADYCARDIA, ATRIAL FLUTTER, ATRIAL FIBRILLATION.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGSTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from EGSTRESC. EGSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for EGSTRESC or EGSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate an ECG was not done, or an ECG measurement was not taken. Should be null if a result exists in EGORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a measurement or test was not performed. Examples: BROKEN EQUIPMENT or SUBJECT REFUSED. Used in conjunction with EGSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGXFN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: File name and path for the external ECG Waveform file.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor who provided the test results.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGLOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The lead used for the measurement, examples, V1, V6, aVR, I, II, III.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of the ECG test. Examples: 12 LEAD STANDARD.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGBLFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGDRVFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records which represent the average of other records, or that do not come from the CRF, or are not as originally collected or received are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If EGDRVFL=Y, then EGORRES could be null, with EGSTRESC, and (if numeric) EGSTRESN having the derived value.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Should be null for records that contain collected or derived data. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, VENDOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date of ECG.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of the ECG, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Text Description of time when measurement should be taken. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See EGTPTNUM and EGTPTREF. Examples: Start, 5 min post.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGTPTNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Numerical version of EGTPT to aid in sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGELTM
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a fixed time point reference (EGTPTREF). Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration. Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by EGTPTREF, or "PT8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by EGTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGTPTREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by EGELTM, EGTPTNUM, and EGTPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EGRFTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of the reference time point, EGTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FAGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor‘s operational database. Example: Line number on a CRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FATESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in FATEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in FATESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g. "1TEST"). FATESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Example: SEV, OCCUR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FATEST
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in FATEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Severity/Intensity, Occurrence

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FAOBJ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to describe the object or focal point of the findings observation that is represented by --TEST. Examples: the term (such as Acne) describing a clinical sign or symptom that is being measured by a Severity test, or an event such as VOMIT where the volume of Vomit is being measured by a VOLUME test.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FACAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a Category of related records. Examples: GERD, PRE-SPECIFIED AE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further Categorization of FACAT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FAORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Result or Finding in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the test as originally received or collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FAORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for FAORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from FAORRES in a standard format or standard units. FASTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in FASTRESN. For example, if a test has results "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in FAORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning; they could be represented in standard format in FASTRESC as "NEGATIVE".

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from FASTRESC. FASTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for FASTRESC and FASTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate that the measurement was not done. Should be null if a result exists in FAORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FAREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a question was not answered. Example: subject refused. Used in conjunction with FASTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FALOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to specify the location of the clinical evaluation. Example: LEFT ARM

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FABLFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FAEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Should be null for records that contain collected or derived data. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, VENDOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FADY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of collection, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics. This formula should be consistent across the submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IESEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IESPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor‘s operational database. Example: Inclusion or Exclusion criteria number from CRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IETESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the criterion described in IETEST. The value in IETESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g."1TEST"). IETESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: IN01, EX01.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IETEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim description of the inclusion or exclusion criterion that was the exception for the subject within the study. IETEST cannot be longer than 200 characters.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IECAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a Category of related records across subjects.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IESCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further Categorization of the exception criterion. Can be used to distinguish criteria for a sub-study or for to categorize as a major or minor exceptions. Examples: MAJOR, MINOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IEORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original response to Inclusion/Exclusion Criterion question. Inclusion or Exclusion criterion met?

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IESTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Description: I/E Criterion Result in Std Format
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Response to Inclusion/Exclusion criterion result in standard format.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IEDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of collection of the inclusion/exclusion exceptions, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics. This formula should be consistent across the submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external specimen identifier. Example: Specimen ID.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor‘s operational database. Example: Line number on the Lab page.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Lab Test or Examination Short Name
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in LBTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in LBTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g."1TEST"). LBTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: ALT, LDH.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. Note any test normally performed by a clinical laboratory is considered a lab test. The value in LBTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Alanine Aminotransferase, Lactate Dehydrogenase.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a Category of related records across subjects. Examples: such as HEMATOLOGY, URINALYSIS, CHEMISTRY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further Categorization of a test Category such as DIFFERENTIAL, COAGULATON, LIVER FUNCTION, ELECTROLYTES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Result or Finding in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for LBORRES. Example: g/L.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBORNRLO
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Reference Range Lower Limit in Orig Unit
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Lower end of reference range for continuous measurements in Original units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBORNRHI
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Reference Range Upper Limit in Orig Unit
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Upper end of reference range for continuous measurements in Original units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from LBORRES in a standard format or standard units. LBSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in LBSTRESN. For example, if a test has results "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in LBORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in LBSTRESC as "NEGATIVE". For other examples, see general assumptions.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBSTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from LBSTRESC. LBSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for LBSTRESC or LBSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBSTNRLO
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Lower end of reference range for continuous measurements for LBSTRESC/LBSTRESN in standardized units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBSTNRHI
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Upper end of reference range for continuous measurements in standardized units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBSTNRC
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Reference Range for Char Rslt-Std Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: For normal range values that are character in ordinal scale or if categorical ranges were supplied (e.g., "-1 to +1", "NEGATIVE TO TRACE").

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBNRIND
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Indicates where the value falls with respect to reference range defined by LBORNRLO and LBORNRHI, LBSTNRLO and LBSTNRHI, or by LBSTNRC. Examples: NORMAL, ABNORMAL, HIGH, LOW. 2. Sponsors should specify in the study metadata (Comments column in the define.xml) whether LBNRIND refers to the Original or standard reference ranges and results. 3. Should not be used to indicate clinical significance.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate exam not done. Should be null if a result exists in LBORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a measurement or test was not performed such as BROKEN EQUIPMENT, SUBJECT REFUSED, or SPECIMEN LOST. Used in conjunction with LBSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The name or identifier of the laboratory that performed the test.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBLOINC
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Dictionary-derived LOINC Code for LBTEST. 2. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBSPEC
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Examples: SERUM, PLASMA, URINE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBSPCCND
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Free or standardized text describing the condition of the specimen e.g. HEMOLYZED, ICTERIC, LIPEMIC etc.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of the test or examination. Examples: EIA (Enzyme Immunoassay), ELECTROPHORESIS, DIPSTICK

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBBLFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBFAST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify fasting status such as Y, N, U, or null if not relevant.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBDRVFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records, or do not come from the CRF, or are not as originally received or collected are examples of records that might be derived for the submission datasets. If LBDRVFL=Y, then LBORRES may be null, with LBSTRESC, and (if numeric) LBSTRESN having the derived value.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBTOX
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description of toxicity quantified by LBTOXGR. The sponsor is expected to provide the name of the scale and version used to map the terms, utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBTOXGR
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Records toxicity grade value using a standard toxicity scale (such as the NCI CTCAE). If value is from a numeric scale, represent only the number (e.g., "2" and not "Grade 2"). The sponsor is expected to provide the name of the scale and version used to map the terms, utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of specimen collection, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics. This formula should be consistent across the submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Text Description of time when specimen should be taken. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See LBTPTNUM and LBTPTREF. Examples: Start, 5 min post.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBTPTNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Numerical version of LBTPT to aid in sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBELTM
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned Elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (LBTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration. Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by LBTPTREF, or "PT8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by LBTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBTPTREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by LBELTM, LBTPTNUM, and LBTPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBRFTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of the reference time point, LBTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain to support relationships within the domain and between domains. In MB, used to link to findings about organisms which are stored in MS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external specimen identifier. Example: Specimen ID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: ORGANISM IDENTIFIER. For organism identification, MBSPID would remain the same each time the same organism is identified in a new specimen.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Microbiology Test or Finding Short Name
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the measurement, test, or finding described in MBTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in MBTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST"). MBTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples for GRAM STAIN findings: GMNROD, GMNCOC, GMSQEPCE, GMPMNLOW. Examples for CULTURE PLATE findings: ORGANISM.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in MBTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: GRAM NEGATIVE RODS, GRAM NEGATIVE COCCI, SQUAMOUS EPITHELIAL CELLS, PMN PER FIELD LOW, ORGANISM PRESENT

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a Category of related records.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a further Categorization of MBCAT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Result or Finding in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the Microbiology measurement or finding as originally received or collected. Examples for GRAM STAIN findings: +3 MODERATE, +2 FEW, <10. Examples for CULTURE PLATE (ORGANISM) findings: KLEBSIELLA PNEUMONIAE, STREPTOCOCCUS PNEUMONIAE PENICILLIN RESISTANT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original unit for MBORRES. Example: mcg/mL

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from MBORRES in a standard format or standard units. MBSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in MBSTRESN. For example, if a test has results "+3 MODERATE", "MOD", and "MODERATE" in MBORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in MBSTRESC as "MODERATE".

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from MBSTRESC. MBSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for MBSTRESC and MBSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBRESCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to categorize the result of a finding in a standard format. Example for ORGANISM finding: INFECTING, COLONIZER, CONTAMINANT, or NORMAL FLORA.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate Microbiology was not done, or a test was not done. Should be null or have a value of NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with MBSTAT when value is NOT DONE. Examples: BROKEN EQUIPMENT or SUBJECT REFUSED.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor who provides the test results.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBLOINC
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Dictionary-derived LOINC Code for MBTEST. 2. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSPEC

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Examples: SPUTUM, BLOOD, PUS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSPCCND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Free or standardized text describing the condition of the specimen. Example: CONTAMINATED.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBLOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Location relevant to the collection of the measurement. Examples: LUNG, VEIN, LEFT KNEE WOUND, ARM ULCER 1, RIGHT THIGH LATERAL

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of the test or examination. Examples: GRAM STAIN, CULTURE PLATE, BROTH.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBBLFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBDRVFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records or some other derivation, and those that do not come from the CRF, are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If MBDRVFL=Y, then MBORRES may be null with MBSTRESC and (if numeric) MBSTRESN having the derived value.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of MB Specimen Collection
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of the specimen collection, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics. This formula should be consistent across the submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Text Description of time when specimen should be taken. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See MBTPTNUM and MBTPTREF. Examples: Start, 5 min post.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBTPTNUM

Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by MBTPTREF, or "PT8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by MBTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBTPTREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by MBELTM, MBTPTNUM, and MBTPT. Example: PREVIOUS DOSE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBRFTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of the reference time point, MBTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study within the submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique subject identifier within the submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DAREFID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DASPID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DATESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.

ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name, corresponding to the topic variable, of the test or examination used to obtain the drug accountability assessment. The value in DATEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Example: Dispensed Amount, Returned Amount.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DACAT

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DASCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DAORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the Drug Accountability assessment as originally received or collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DAORRESU

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DASTRESN

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DAREASND

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterality, for example, LEFT, RIGHT, BILATERAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TUDIR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing directionality, for example, UPPER, INTERIOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TUPORTOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing the distribution which means arrangement of, or apportioning of, for example, ENTIRE, SINGLE, SEGMENT, MANY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TUMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method used to identify the tumor. Examples: MRI, CT SCAN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TUEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, INDEPENDNT ASSESSOR This column can be left Null when the Investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain. However the column should contain no Null values when data from one or more independent assessors is included meaning that the rows attributed to the Investigator should contain a value of INVESTIGATOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TUEVALID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The Evaluator Specified variable is used in conjunction with TUEVAL to provide an additional level of detail. When multiple assessors play the role identified in TUEVAL, values of TUEVALID will attribute a row of data to a particular assessor. TUEVALID should not contain the names of the assessors, or a code identifier for a specific assessor, but should contain values such as RADIOLOGIST, RADIOLOGIST 1 or RADIOLOGIST 2. The TUEVALID is subject to CDISC Controlled Terminology. See Assumption 7.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TUACPTFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: In cases where more than one independent assessor (e.g. RADIOLOGIST 1, RADIOLOGIST 2, ADJUDICATOR) provide independent assessments at the same time point this flag identifies the record that is considered to be the accepted assessment.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EPOCH
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Epoch associated with the Element in the planned sequence of Elements for the ARM to which the subject was assigned.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TUDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: TUDTC variable represents the date of the scan/image/physical exam not the date that the image was read to identify tumors. TUDTC variable does not represent the VISIT date.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TUDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of the scan/image/physical exam, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness within a dataset for a subject. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external identifier.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-Defined Identifier

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRLNKID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to link the assessment result records to the individual tumor identification record in TU domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRLNKGRP
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to group and link all of the measurement/assessment records used in the assessment of the response record in the RS domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the TEST in TRTEST. TRTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: TUMSTATE, DIAMETER. See Assumption 2.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in TRTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Tumor State, Diameter, Longest Perpendicular diameter, Volume, Area. See Assumption 2.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Result or Finding in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the Tumor measurement/assessment as originally received or collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for TRORRES. Example: mm

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from TRORRES in a standard format or standard units. TRSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in TRSTRESN

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRSTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from TRSTRESC. TRSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for TRSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a scan/image/physical exam was not performed or a tumor measurement was not taken. Should be Null if a result exists in TRORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a scan/image/physical exam was not performed or a tumor measurement was not taken. Examples: SCAN NOT PERFORMED, NOT ASSESSABLE: Image obscured, TUMOR. Used in conjunction with TRSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The name or identifier of the vendor that performed the Tumor measurement or assessment. This column can be left Null when the Investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Method used to Identify the Tumor
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method used to measure the tumor. Examples: MRI, CT SCAN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TREVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR. This column can be left Null when the Investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain. However the column should contain no Null values when data from one or more independent assessors is included meaning that the rows attributed to the Investigator should contain a value of INVESTIGATOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness within a dataset for a subject. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external identifier.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined identifier.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSLNKID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to link the response assessment to the appropriate measurement records (in TR) for same tumor that was used to determine the response result.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSLNKGRP
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to link the response assessment to the all of the measurement/assessment records in the TR domain which were used in the assessment of the response.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the TEST in RSTEST. RSTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: TRGRESP, NTRGRESP, OVRRESP, BESTRESP, NRADPROG

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the response assessment. The value in RSTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Target Response, Non-target Response, Overall Response, Best Overall Response, Non-radiological progression (i.e. Symptomatic deterioration)

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: RSCAT is used to identify the criteria used in the assessment of response and a version number if appropriate

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the Response assessment as originally received, collected, or calculated.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Response Assessment Result in Std Format
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for the response assessment, copied or derived from RSORRES in a standard format or standard units. RSSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate the response assessment was not performed. Should be Null if a result exists in RSORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a response assessment was not performed. Examples: All target tumors not evaluated, Subject does not have non-target tumors. Used in conjunction with RSSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The name or identifier of the vendor that performed the response assessment. This column can be left Null when the Investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR. This column can be left Null when the Investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain. However the column should contain no Null values when data from one or more independent assessors is included meaning that the rows attributed to the Investigator should contain a value of INVESTIGATOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSEVALID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The Evaluator Specified variable is used in conjunction with RSEVAL to provide an additional level of detail. When multiple assessors play the role identified in RSEVAL, values of RSEVALID will attribute a row of data to a particular assessor. RSEVALID should not contain the names of the assessors, or a code identifier for a specific assessor. The RSEVALID variable is subject to CDISC Controlled Terminology. Examples: RADIOLOGIST, RADIOLOGIST 1 or RADIOLOGIST 2. See Assumption 4

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSACPTFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: In cases where more than one independent assessor (e.g. RADIOLOGIST 1, RADIOLOGIST 2, ADJUDICATOR) provides an evaluation of response this flag identifies the record that is considered to be the accepted evaluation.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EPOCH
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Epoch associated with the Element in the planned sequence of Elements for the ARM to which the subject was assigned

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: RSDTC may be derived from the dates of scans/images/physical exams which may be performed on different dates. However, if all assessments are performed on the same date, RSDTC may be consistent with the TUDTC and TRDTC. Note the physical exam date may correspond to the visit date.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of the response assessment, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of the test or examination. Examples: EIA (Enzyme Immunoassay), ELECTROPHORESIS, DIPSTICK

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBBLFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be Y or null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBFAST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify fasting status such as Y, N, U, or null if not relevant.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBDRVFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records, or do not come from the CRF, or are not as originally received or collected are examples of records that might be derived for the submission datasets. If LBDRVFL=Y, then LBORRES may be null, with LBSTRESC, and (if numeric) LBSTRESN having the derived value.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBTOX
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description of toxicity quantified by LBTOXGR. The sponsor is expected to provide the name of the scale and version used to map the terms, utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBTOXGR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Records toxicity grade value using a standard toxicity scale (such as the NCI CTCAE). If value is from a numeric scale, represent only the number (e.g., 2 and not Grade 2). The sponsor is expected to provide the name of the scale and version used to map the terms, utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of specimen collection, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics. This formula should be consistent across the submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Text Description of time when specimen should be taken. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See LBTPTNUM and LBTPTREF. Examples: Start, 5 min post.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBTPTNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Numerical version of LBTPT to aid in sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBELTM
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned Elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (LBTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration. Examples: -PT15M to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by LBTPTREF, or PT8H to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by LBTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBTPTREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by LBELTM, LBTPTNUM, and LBTPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: LBRFTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of the reference time point, LBTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain to support relationships within the domain and between domains. In MB, used to link to findings about organisms which are stored in MS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external specimen identifier. Example: Specimen ID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: ORGANISM IDENTIFIER. For organism identification, MBSPID would remain the same each time the same organism is identified in a new specimen.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Microbiology Test or Finding Short Name
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the measurement, test, or finding described in MBTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in MBTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., 1TEST). MBTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples for GRAM STAIN findings: GMNROD, GMNCOC, GMSQEPCE, GMPMNLOW. Examples for CULTURE PLATE findings: ORGANISM.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in MBTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: GRAM NEGATIVE RODS, GRAM NEGATIVE COCCI, SQUAMOUS EPITHELIAL CELLS, PMN PER FIELD LOW, ORGANISM PRESENT

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of related records.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a further categorization of MBCAT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Result or Finding in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the Microbiology measurement or finding as originally received or collected. Examples for GRAM STAIN findings: +3 MODERATE, +2 FEW, <10. Examples for CULTURE PLATE (ORGANISM) findings: KLEBSIELLA PNEUMONIAE, STREPTOCOCCUS PNEUMONIAE PENICILLIN RESISTANT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original unit for MBORRES. Example: mcg/mL

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from MBORRES in a standard format or standard units. MBSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in MBSTRESN. For example, if a test has results +3 MODERATE, MOD, and MODERATE in MBORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in MBSTRESC as MODERATE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from MBSTRESC. MBSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for MBSTRESC and MBSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBRESCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to categorize the result of a finding in a standard format. Example for ORGANISM finding: INFECTING, COLONIZER, CONTAMINANT, or NORMAL FLORA.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate Microbiology was not done, or a test was not done. Should be null or have a value of NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with MBSTAT when value is NOT DONE. Examples: BROKEN EQUIPMENT or SUBJECT REFUSED.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor who provides the test results.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBLOINC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Dictionary-derived LOINC Code for MBTEST. 2. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSPEC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Examples: SPUTUM, BLOOD, PUS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBSPCCND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Free or standardized text describing the condition of the specimen. Example: CONTAMINATED.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBLOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Location relevant to the collection of the measurement. Examples: LUNG, VEIN, LEFT KNEE WOUND, ARM ULCER 1, RIGHT THIGH LATERAL

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of the test or examination. Examples: GRAM STAIN, CULTURE PLATE, BROTH.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBBLFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be Y or null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBDRVFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records or some other derivation, and those that do not come from the CRF, are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If MBDRVFL=Y, then MBORRES may be null with MBSTRESC and (if numeric) MBSTRESN having the derived value.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of MB Specimen Collection
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of the specimen collection, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics. This formula should be consistent across the submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Text Description of time when specimen should be taken. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See MBTPTNUM and MBTPTREF. Examples: Start, 5 min post.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBTPTNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Numerical version of MBTPT to aid in sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBELTM
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (MBTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration. Examples: -PT15M to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by MBTPTREF, or PT8H to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by MBTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBTPTREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by MBELTM, MBTPTNUM, and MBTPT. Example: PREVIOUS DOSE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MBRFTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of the reference time point, MBTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain to support relationships within the domain and between domains. In MS, used to link to organism in MB.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external specimen identifier. Example: Specimen ID.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the measurement, test, or finding described in MSTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in MSTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g.1TEST). MSTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples for GROWTH findings: EXTGROW, COLCOUNT. For SUSCEPTIBILITY findings, the test is the drug the organism was tested with, i.e. PENICLLN, AMOXCLLN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. Examples for GROWTH findings: Extent of Growth, Colony Count. Examples for SUSCEPTIBILITY findings: Amoxicillin Susceptibility, Penicillin Susceptibility

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of related records. Examples: GROWTH, SUSCEPTIBILITY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further categorization of a test category. Examples: CULTURE, ISOLATE

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSORRES

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSORRESU

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for MSSTRESC and MSSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSRESCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to categorize the result of a finding in a standard format. Example for SUSCEPTIBILITY finding: SUSCEPTIBLE, INTERMEDIATE, RESISTANT, or UNKNOWN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a test on an organism was not done, or a test was not performed. Should be null if a result exists in MSORRES or have a value of NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSREASND

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSLOINC

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSMETHOD
