ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSELTM
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (MSTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date time variable. Examples: -PT15M to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by MSTPTREF, or P8H to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by MSTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MSTPTREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by MSELTM, MSTPTNUM, and MSTPT. Example: PREVIOUS DOSE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MISEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MIGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject. This is not the treatment group number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MIREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external specimen identifier. Example: Specimen barcode number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MISPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number from the MI Findings page.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MITESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in MITEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in MITESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., 1TEST is not valid). MITESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: HER2, BRCA1, TTF1.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MITEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in MITEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Human Epidermal Growth Factor Receptor 2, Breast Cancer Susceptibility Gene 1, Thyroid Transcription Factor 1.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MITSTDTL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Further description of the test performed in producing the MI result. This would be used to represent specific attributes, such as intensity score or percentage of cells displaying presence of the biomarker or compound

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MICAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of related records.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MISCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a further categorization of MICAT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MIORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Result or Finding in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the histopathology measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MIORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original unit for MIORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MISTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from MIORRES in a standard format or standard units. MISTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in MISTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MISTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from MISTRESC. MISTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MISTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for MISTRESC and MISTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MIRESCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to categorize the result of a finding. Examples: MALIGNANT or BENIGN for tumor findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MISTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate examination not done or result is missing. Should be null if a result exists in MIORRES or have a value of NOT DONE when MIORRES=NULL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MIREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with MISTAT when value is NOT DONE. Examples: SAMPLE AUTOLYZED, SPECIMEN LOST.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MINAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name or identifier of the vendor (e.g., laboratory) that provided the test results.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MISPEC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Subject of the observation. Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Examples: TISSUE, BLOOD, BONE MARROW.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MISPCCND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Free or standardized text describing the condition of the specimen. Example: AUTOLYZED.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MILOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Location relevant to the collection of the specimen. Examples: LUNG, KNEE JOINT, ARM, THIGH.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MILAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for laterality of the location of the specimen in MILOC. Examples: LEFT, RIGHT, BILATERAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MIDIR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for directionality of the location of the specimen in MILOC. Examples: DORSAL, PROXIMAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MIMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of the test or examination. This could include the technique or type of staining used for the slides. Examples: IHC, Crystal Violet, Safranin, Trypan Blue, or Propidium Iodide.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MIBLFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be Y or null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MIEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Example: PATHOLOGIST, PEER REVIEW, SPONSOR PATHOLOGIST.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MIDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of specimen collection, in ISO 8601 format.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MIDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of specimen collection, in integer days. The algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in the Demographics (DM) domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external procedure identifier.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number from the procedure or test page.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOLNKID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to link results of a procedure to the procedure performed.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in MOTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in MOTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., 1TEST). MOTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: VOLUME, INTP

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in MOTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Volume, Interpretation

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to categorize observations across subjects.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further categorization.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOPOS
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Position of the subject during a measurement or examination. Examples: SUPINE, STANDING, SITTING.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Result or Finding in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the procedure measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for MOORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from MOORRES in a standard format or standard units. MOSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in MOSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOSTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from MOSTRESC. MOSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for MOSTRESC or MOSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a test was not done, or a measurement was not taken. Should be null if a result exists in MOORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a measurement or test was not performed. Examples: BROKEN EQUIPMENT or SUBJECT REFUSED. Used in conjunction with MOSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOXFN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: File path to the external file.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MONAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor who provided the test results.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOLOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Location relevant to the collection of the measurement. Examples: BRAIN, KIDNEY, LIVER. etc.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOLAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for laterality of the specimen within the subject for paired specimens. Examples: LEFT, RIGHT, BILATERAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MODIR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for directionality of the specimen within the subject. Examples: DORSAL, PROXIMAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOPORTOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing the portion of totality which means arrangement of, or apportioning of. Examples: ENTIRE, PARTIAL

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of the test or examination result.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOANMETH
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Analysis method applied to obtain a summarized result. Examples: STEREOLOGY

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOBLFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be Y or null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MODRVFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records, or that do not come from the CRF, or are not as originally collected or received are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If MODRVFL=Y, then MOORRES could be null, and (if numeric) MOSTRESN having the derived value.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Should be null for records that contain collected or derived data. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, VENDOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MODTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date of test.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MODY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of the procedure or test, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Text Description of time when measurement should be taken. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See MOTPTNUM and MOTPTREF. Examples: Start, 5 min post.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOTPTNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Numerical version of MOTPT to aid in sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOELTM
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a fixed time point reference (MOTPTREF). Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration. Examples: -PT15M to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by MOTPTREF, or PT8H to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by MOTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MOTPTREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by MOELTM, MOTPTNUM, and MOTPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: MORFTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of the reference time point, MOTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique subject identifier within the submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain to support relationships within the domain and between domains.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external specimen identifier. Example: Specimen ID.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the analyte or specimen characteristic. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in PCTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., 1TEST). PCTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: ASA, VOL, SPG.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the analyte or specimen characteristic. Note any test normally performed by a clinical laboratory is considered a lab test. The value in PCTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Acetylsalicylic Acid, Volume, Specific Gravity.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of related records. Examples: ANALYTE, SPECIMEN PROPERTY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further categorization of a test category.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Result or Finding in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for PCORRES. Example: mg/L.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from PCORRES in a standard format or standard units. PCSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in PCSTRESN. For example, if a test has results NONE, NEG, and NEGATIVE in PCORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in PCSTRESC as NEGATIVE. For other examples, see general assumptions.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCSTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from PCSTRESC. PCSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for PCSTRESC and PCSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a result was not obtained. Should be null if a result exists in PCORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a result was not obtained such as SPECIMEN LOST. Used in conjunction with PCSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor who provides the test results.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCSPEC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Examples: SERUM, PLASMA, URINE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCSPCCND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Free or standardized text describing the condition of the specimen e.g. HEMOLYZED, ICTERIC, LIPEMIC etc.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of the test or examination. Examples include HPLC/MS, ELISA. This should contain sufficient information and granularity to allow differentiation of various methods that might have been used within a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCFAST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify fasting status.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCDRVFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records, which do not come from the CRF, are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If PCDRVFL=Y, then PCORRES should be null with PCSTRESC, and (if numeric) PCSTRESN having the derived value.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCLLOQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicates the lower limit of quantitation for an assay. Units should be those used in PCSTRESU.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of specimen collection represented in ISO 8601 character format. If there is no end time, then this will be the collection time.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: End date/time of specimen collection represented in ISO 8601 character format. If there is no end time, the collection time should be stored in PCDTC, and PCENDTC should be null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Actual Study Day of Specimen Collection
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of specimen collection, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Text Description of time when specimen should be taken. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See PCTPTNUM and PCTPTREF. Examples: Start, 5 min post.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCTPTNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Numerical version of PCTPT to aid in sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCELTM
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (PCTPTREF) such as PREVIOUS DOSE or PREVIOUS MEAL. This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date time variable.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCTPTREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the fixed reference point used as a basis for PCTPT, PCTPTNUM, and PCELTM. Example: Most Recent Dose.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCRFTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of the reference time point described by PCTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PCEVLINT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Evaluation Interval associated with a PCTEST record represented in ISO 8601 character format. Example: -P2H to represent an interval of 2 hours prior to a PCTPT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique subject identifier within the submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain to support relationships within the domain and between domains.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the pharmacokinetic parameter. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in PPTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., 1TEST). PPTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: AUC, TMAX, CMAX.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the pharmacokinetic parameter. The value in PPTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: AUC, Tmax, Cmax.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of related records. For PP, this should be the name of the analyte in PCTEST whose profile the parameter is associated with.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Categorization of the model type used to calculate the PK parameters. Examples include COMPARTMENTAL, NON-COMPARTMENTAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Result or Finding in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for PPORRES. Example: ng/L.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from PPORRES in a standard format or standard units. PPSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in PPSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from PPSTRESC. PPSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for PPSTRESC and PPSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate that a parameter was not calculated. Should be null if a result exists in PPORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a parameter was not calculated, such as INSUFFICIENT DATA. Used in conjunction with PPSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPSPEC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. If multiple specimen types are used for a calculation (e.g., serum and urine for renal clearance), then this field should be left blank. Examples: SERUM, PLASMA, URINE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Nominal date/time of parameter calculations.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PPRFTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of the reference time point from the PC records used to calculate a parameter record. The values in PPRFTDTC should be the same as that in PCRFTDTC for related records.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PESEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PESPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a CRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PETESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in PETEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in PETESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g.1TEST). PETESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PETEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim term part of the body examined. The value in PETEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Cardiovascular and Respiratory. For subject-level exam, value should be Physical Examination.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEMODIFY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: If PEORRES is modified as part of a defined procedure, then PEMODIFY will contain the modified text.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PECAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of examination. Examples: GENERAL, NEUROLOGICAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PESCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further categorization of the examination. Used if needed to add further detail to PECAT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEBODSYS
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Body system or organ class ( MedDRA SOC) that is involved in a measurement from the standard hierarchy (e.g., MedDRA).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Text description of any abnormal findings. If the examination was completed and there were no abnormal findings, the value should be NORMAL. If the examination was not performed on a particular body system, or at the subject level, then the value should be null, and NOT DONE should appear in PESTAT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for PEORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PESTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: If there are findings for a body system, then either the dictionary preferred term (if findings are coded using a dictionary) or PEORRES (if findings are not coded) should appear here. If PEORRES is null, PESTRESC should be null

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PESTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate exam not done. Should be null if a result exists in PEORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why an examination was not performed or why a body system was not examined. Example: SUBJECT REFUSED. Used in conjunction with STAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PELOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Can be used to specify where a physical exam finding occurred. Example: LEFT ARM for skin rash.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of the test or examination. Examples: XRAY, MRI.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Should be null for records that contain collected or derived data. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, VENDOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PEDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of physical exam, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSTESTCD

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the question or group of questions used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in QSTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Example: In General, How is Your Health?

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of related records that will be meaningful to the Reviewer. Examples: HAMILTON DEPRESSION SCALE, SF36, ADAS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further categorization of the questions within the category. Examples: MENTAL HEALTH DOMAIN, DEPRESSION DOMAIN, WORD RECALL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Finding as originally received or collected (e.g. RARELY, SOMETIMES). When sponsors apply codelist to indicate the code values are statistically meaningful standardized scores, which are defined by sponsors or by valid methodologies such as SF36 questionnaires, QSORRES will contain the decode format, and QSSTRESC and QSSTRESN may contain the standardized code values or scores.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for QSORRES, such as minutes or seconds or the units associated with a visual analog scale.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the finding for all questions or sub-scores, copied or derived from QSORRES in a standard format or standard units. QSSTRESC should store all findings in character format; if findings are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in QSSTRESN. If question scores are derived from the original finding, then the standard format is the score. Examples: 0, 1. When sponsors apply codelist to indicate the code values are statistically meaningful standardized scores, which are defined by sponsors or by valid methodologies such as SF36 questionnaires, QSORRES will contain the decode format, and QSSTRESC and QSSTRESN may contain the standardized code values or scores.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSSTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from QSSTRESC. QSSTRESN should store all numeric results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for QSSTRESC or QSSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a questionnaire or response to a questionnaire was not done. Should be null if a result exists in QSORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a question was not answered. Used in conjunction with QSSTAT when value is NOT DONE. Example: SUBJECT REFUSED.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSBLFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be Y or null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSDRVFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records or questionnaire sub-scores that do not come from the CRF are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If QSDRVFL=Y, then QSORRES may be null with QSSTRESC and (if numeric) QSSTRESN having the derived value.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSELTM
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSRFTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of the reference time point, LBTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QSEVLINT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Evaluation Interval associated with a QSTEST question represented in ISO 8601 character format. Example: -P2Y to represent an interval of 2 years in the question Have you experienced any episodes in the past 2 years?

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRSTAT

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a scan/image/physical exam was not performed or a tumor measurement was not taken. Examples: SCAN NOT PERFORMED, NOT ASSESSABLE: Image obscured, TUMOR. Used in conjunction with TRSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The name or identifier of the vendor that performed the Tumor measurement or assessment. This column can be left Null when the Investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TRMETHOD

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TREVAL

However the column should contain no Null values when data from one or more independent assessors is included meaning that the rows attributed to the Investigator should contain a value of INVESTIGATOR.

The TREVALID variable is subject to CDISC Controlled Terminology. Note TREVAL must also be populated when TREVALID is populated. See Assumption 7.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external identifier.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSSPID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSLNKID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSLNKGRP
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to link the response assessment to the all of the measurement/assessment records in the TR domain which were used in the assessment of the response.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the TEST in RSTEST. RSTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: TRGRESP, NTRGRESP, OVRRESP, BESTRESP, NRADPROG

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the response assessment. The value in RSTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Target Response, Non-target Response, Overall Response, Best Overall Response, Non-radiological progression (i.e. Symptomatic deterioration)

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: RSCAT is used to identify the criteria used in the assessment of response and a version number if appropriate

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the Response assessment as originally received, collected, or calculated.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSSTRESC

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for the response assessment, copied or derived from RSORRES in a standard format or standard units. RSSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format;

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate the response assessment was not performed. Should be Null if a result exists in RSORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a response assessment was not performed. Examples: All target tumors not evaluated, Subject does not have non-target tumors. Used in conjunction with RSSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The name or identifier of the vendor that performed the response assessment. This column can be left Null when the Investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR. This column can be left Null when the Investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain. However the column should contain no Null values when data from one or more independent assessors is included meaning that the rows attributed to the Investigator should contain a value of INVESTIGATOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RSEVALID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The Evaluator Specified variable is used in conjunction with RSEVAL to provide an additional level of detail. ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXTRTV

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXVAMT

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXVAMTU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Units of the treatment vehicle amount indicated by EXVAMT

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXADJ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes reason or explanation of why a dose is adjusted - used only when an adjustment is represented in EX.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TAETORD
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Order of Element within Arm

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXSTDTC

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The time when administration of the treatment indicated by EXTRT and EXDOSE ended.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXSTDY

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXENDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of End of Treatment
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of end of treatment relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Collected duration and unit of a treatment. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Text Description of time when a dose should be given.2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See EXTPTNUM and EXTPTREF. Examples: Start or 5 min post.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXELTM
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external identifier (e.g., kit number, bottle label, vial identifier).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a CRF Page.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECLNKID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to link related records across domains.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECLNKGRP
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to link related, grouped records across domains.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECTRT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the intervention treatment known to the subject and/or administrator.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECMOOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Mode or condition of the record specifying whether the intervention (activity) is intended to happen or has happened. Values align with BRIDG pillars (e.g., scheduled context, performed context) and HL7 activity moods (e.g., intent, event). Examples: SCHEDULED, PERFORMED. CDISC Controlled Terminology request for MOOD codelist with values of SCHEDULED and PERFORMED has been submitted.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of related ECTRT values.

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further categorization of ECCAT values.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECPRESP
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used when a specific intervention is pre-specified. Values should be Y or null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECOCCUR

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECDOSTXT

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECDOSU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Units for ECDOSE, ECDOSTOT, or ECDOSTXT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECDOSFRM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Dose form for ECTRT. Examples: TABLET, LOTION.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECDOSFRQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of ECDOSE within a specific time period. Examples: Q2H, QD, BID.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECDOSTOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Total daily dose of ECTRT using the units in ECDOSU. Used when dosing is collected as Total Daily Dose.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECDOSRGM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Text description of the intended schedule or regimen for the Intervention. Example: TWO WEEKS ON, TWO WEEKS OFF.

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Route of administration for the intervention. Examples: ORAL, INTRAVENOUS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECLOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Lot Number of the ECTRT product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECLOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Specifies location of administration. Example: ARM, LIP.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECLAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing laterality of the intervention administration. Examples: LEFT, RIGHT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECDIR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing directionality. Examples: ANTERIOR, LOWER, PROXIMAL, UPPER.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECPORTOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing distribution, which means arrangement of, apportioning of. Examples: ENTIRE, SINGLE, SEGMENT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECFAST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify fasting status. Examples: Y, N.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECPSTRG
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Amount of an active ingredient expressed quantitatively per dosage unit, per unit of volume, or per unit of weight, according to the pharmaceutical dose form.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECPSTRGU

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ECADJ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes reason or explanation of why a dose is adjusted.

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Numerical version of ECTPT to aid in sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to facilitate identification of relationships between records.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PROCCUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to record whether a pre-specified procedure occurred when information about the occurrence of a specific procedure is solicited.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PRINDC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Denotes the indication for the procedure (e.g., why the procedure was performed).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PRSTRTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Start Relative to Reference Time Point
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifies the start of the observation as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable PRSTTPT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PRSTTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the sponsor-defined reference point referred to by PRSTRTPT. Examples: 2003-12-15 or VISIT 1.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PRENRTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Description: End Relative to Reference Time Point
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifies the end of the observation as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable PRENTPT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: PRENTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the sponsor-defined reference point referred to by PRENRTPT. Examples: 2003-12-25 or VISIT 2.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a Tobacco & Alcohol use CRF page.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUTRT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Substance name. Examples: Cigarettes, Coffee.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUMODIFY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: If SUTRT is modified, then the modified text is placed here.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUDECOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized or dictionary-derived text description of SUTRT or SUMODIFY if the sponsor chooses to code the substance use. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of related records. Examples: TOBACCO, ALCOHOL, or CAFFEINE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further categorization of substance use. Examples: CIGARS, CIGARETTES, BEER, WINE

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUPRESP
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate whether (Y/null) information about the use of a specific substance was solicited on the CRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUOCCUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: When the use of specific substances is solicited, SUOCCUR is used to indicate whether or not (Y/N) a particular pre-specified substance was used. Values are null for substances not specifically solicited.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: When the use of pre-specified substances is solicited, the completion status indicates that there was no response to the question about the pre-specified substance. When there is no pre-specified list on the CRF, then the completion status indicates that substance use was not assessed for the subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes the reason substance use was not collected. Used in conjunction with SUSTAT when value of SUSTAT is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUCLAS
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Substance use class. May be obtained from coding. When coding to a single class, populate with class value. If using a dictionary and coding to multiple classes, then follow assumption 4.1.3.5 or omit SUCLAS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUCLASCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Code corresponding to SUCLAS. May be obtained from coding.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUDOSE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Amount of SUTRT consumed.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUDOSTXT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Substance use consumption amounts or a range of consumption information collected in text form.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUDOSU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Units for SUDOSE, SUDOSTXT, and SUDOSTOT. Examples: OUNCES, CIGARETTE EQUIVALENTS, or GRAMS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUDOSFRM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Dose form for SUTRT. Examples: INJECTABLE, LIQUID, or POWDER.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUDOSFRQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of SUDOSE within a specific time period. Example: Q24H (every day)

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUDOSTOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Total daily use of SUTRT using the units in SUDOSU. If sponsor needs to aggregate the data over a period other than daily, then the aggregated total could be recorded in a Supplemental Qualifier variable.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUROUTE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Route of administration for SUTRT. Examples: ORAL, INTRAVENOUS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUSTDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of Start of Substance Use
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of start of substance use relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUENDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of End of Substance Use
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of end of substance use relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUDUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Collected duration of substance use in ISO 8601 format. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUSTRF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes the start of the substance use relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). If information such as PRIOR, ONGOING, or CONTINUING was collected, this information may be translated into SUSTRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUENRF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes the end of the substance use with relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). If information such as PRIOR, ONGOING, or CONTINUING was collected, this information may be translated into SUENRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUSTTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by SUSTRTPT. Examples: 2003-12-15 or VISIT 1.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUENRTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Description: End Relative to Reference Time Point
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifies the end of the medication as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable SUENTPT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUENTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by SUENRTPT. Examples: 2003-12-25 or VISIT 2.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SPDEVID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXSEQ

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXGRPID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXSPID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXDOSU

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXDOSFRQ

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXDOSTOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Total daily exposure of DXTRT using the units in DXDOSU

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXDOSRGM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Text description of the (intended) schedule or regimen for the Intervention.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXROUTE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Route of administration for DXTRT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXLOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Anatomic location of exposure

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXLAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing laterality

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of device exposure.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXADJ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes reason why the exposure was adjusted from protocol-specified or expected exposure levels.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXSTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Start date and time of exposure

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: End date and time of exposure.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXSTDY

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXENDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of End of Device Exposure
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of end of exposure

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXDUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Collected duration for a treatment episode.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXSPID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXTRT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the intervention treatment — usually the verbatim name of the investigational treatment given during the dosing period for the observation.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a Category of related records. Example: COMPARATOR CLASS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further Categorization of treatment.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Amount of EXTRT administered or given.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSTXT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Dosing amounts or a range of dosing information collected in text form. Example: 200-400.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Units for EXDOSE and EXDOSTOT. Examples: ng, mg, or mg/kg.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSFRM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Dose form for EXTRT. Examples: TABLET, LOTION.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSFRQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of EXDOSE within a specific time period. Examples: BID (twice daily), Q4S (once every four weeks), BIS (twice a week).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSTOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Total daily dose of EXTRT using the units in EXDOSU. Total dose over a period other than day could be recorded in a separate Supplemental Qualifier variable.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSRGM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Text description of the (intended) schedule or regimen for the Intervention. Examples: TWO WEEKS ON, TWO WEEKS OFF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXROUTE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Route of administration for EXTRT. Examples: ORAL, INTRAVENOUS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXLOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Lot Number of the EXTRT product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXLOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Specifies location of administration. Example: LEFT ARM for a topical application.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXTRTV
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes vehicle used for treatment. Example: SALINE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXVAMT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Amount administered of the treatment vehicle indicated by EXTRTV

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXVAMTU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Units of the treatment vehicle amount indicated by EXVAMT

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXADJ
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes reason or explanation of why a dose is adjusted – used only when an adjustment is represented in EX.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TAETORD
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Order of Element within Arm
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Number that gives the order of the Element within the Arm.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EPOCH
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Trial Epoch of the Exposure record. Examples: SCREENING, TREATMENT PHASE, FOLLOW-UP

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXSTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The time when administration of the treatment indicated by EXTRT and EXDOSE began.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The time when administration of the treatment indicated by EXTRT and EXDOSE ended.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXSTDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of Start of Treatment
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of start of treatment relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXENDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of End of Treatment
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of end of treatment relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Collected duration and unit of a treatment. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Text Description of time when a dose should be given. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See EXTPTNUM and EXTPTREF. Examples: Start or 5 min post.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXTPTNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Numerical version of EXTPT to aid in sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXELTM
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601 format) relative to the planned fixed reference (EXTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time. Represented as an ISO duration.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXTPTREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by EXELTM, EXTPTNUM, and EXTPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.
