ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Examples: a number pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or record identifier defined in the sponsor‘s operational database. Example: line number on a concomitant medication page.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMTRT
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Reported Name of Drug, Med, or Therapy
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim medication name that is either pre-printed or collected on a CRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMMODIFY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: If CMTRT is modified to facilitate coding, then CMMODIFY will contain the modified text.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDECOD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized or dictionary-derived text description of CMTRT or CMMODIFY. Equivalent to the generic medication name in WHO Drug. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes. If an intervention term does not have a decode value in the dictionary then CMDECOD will be left blank.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a Category of medications/treatments. Examples: PRIOR, CONCOMITANT, ANTI-CANCER MEDICATION, or GENERAL CONMED.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further Categorization of medications/ treatment. Examples: CHEMOTHERAPY, HORMONAL THERAPY, ALTERNATIVE THERAPY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMPRESP
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate whether (Y/null) information about the use of a specific medication was solicited on the CRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMOCCUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: When the use of specific medications is solicited, CMOCCUR is used to indicate whether or not (Y/N) use of the medication occurred. Values are null for medications not specifically solicited.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate that a question about a pre-specified medication was not answered. Should be null or have a value of NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes the reason concomitant medication was not collected. Used in conjunction with CMSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMINDC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Denotes why a medication was taken or administered. Examples: NAUSEA, HYPERTENSION.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMCLAS
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Drug class. May be obtained from coding. When coding to a single class, populate with class value. If using a dictionary and coding to multiple classes, then follow assumption 4.1.2.8.3 or omit CMCLAS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMCLASCD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Class code corresponding to CMCLAS. Drug class. May be obtained from coding. When coding to a single class, populate with class code. If using a dictionary and coding to multiple classes, then follow assumption 4.1.2.8.3 or omit CMCLASCD.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Amount of CMTRT taken.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSTXT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Dosing amounts or a range of dosing information collected in text form. Units may be stored in CMDOSU. Example: 200-400, 15-20.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Units for CMDOSE, CMDOSTXT, and CMDOSTOT. Examples: ng, mg, or mg/kg.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSFRM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Dose form for CMTRT. Examples: TABLET, LOTION.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSFRQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of CMDOSE within a specific time period. Examples: BID (twice daily), Q12H (every 12 hours).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSTOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Total daily dose of CMTRT using the units in CMDOSU. Total dose over a period other than day could be recorded in a separate Supplemental Qualifier variable. CMDOSTOT should be used in addition to CMDOSE, and not in place of it.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSRGM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Text description of the (intended) schedule or regimen for the Intervention. Examples: TWO WEEKS ON, TWO WEEKS OFF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMROUTE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Route of administration for CMTRT. Examples: ORAL, INTRAVENOUS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSTDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of Start of Medication
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of start of medication relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMENDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of End of Medication
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of end of medication relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Collected duration for a treatment episode. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSTRF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes the start of the medication relative to sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). If information such as "PRIOR", "ONGOING", or "CONTINUING" was collected, this information may be translated into CMSTRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMENRF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes the end of the medication relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). If information such as "PRIOR", "ONGOING", or "CONTINUING" was collected, this information may be translated into CMENRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSTRTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Start Relative to Reference Time Point
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifies the start of the medication as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable CMSTTPT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSTTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by CMSTRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-15" or "VISIT 1".

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMENRTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Description: End Relative to Reference Time Point
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifies the end of the medication as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable CMENTPT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMENTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by CMENRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-25" or "VISIT 2".

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SPDEVID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined identifier for the device.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of device records within subject records within a domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier that ties together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXTRT
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Name of Device Exposure or Output
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the device or the exposure outputs that are delivered or administered via the device. This should match the definitions as described in the trial summary domain and/or the protocol.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a Category of device exposures

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further Categorization of device exposures

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXDOSE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Amount of DXTRT administered/delivered per administration.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXDOSTXT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Exposure amounts or a range of exposure information collected in text form.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXDOSU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Units for DXDOSE, DXDOSTXT, and DXDOSTOT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXDOSFRQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Exposure frequency per interval.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXDOSTOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Total daily exposure of DXTRT using the units in DXDOSU

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXDOSRGM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Text description of the (intended) schedule or regimen for the Intervention.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXROUTE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Route of administration for DXTRT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXLOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Anatomic location of exposure

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXLAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing laterality

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of device exposure.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXADJ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes reason why the exposure was adjusted from protocol-specified or expected exposure levels.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXSTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Start date and time of exposure

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: End date and time of exposure.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXSTDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of Start of Device Exposure
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of start of exposure.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXENDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of End of Device Exposure
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of end of exposure

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DXDUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Collected duration for a treatment episode.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Examples: a number pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or record identifier defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: line number on a concomitant medication page.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMTRT
ProSDTMVariable.Description: "Reported Name of Drug, Med, or Therapy"
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim medication name that is either pre-printed or collected on a CRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMMODIFY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: If CMTRT is modified to facilitate coding, then CMMODIFY will contain the modified text.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDECOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized or dictionary-derived text description of CMTRT or CMMODIFY. Equivalent to the generic medication name in WHO Drug. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes. If an intervention term does not have a decode value in the dictionary then CMDECOD will be left blank.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of medications/treatments. Examples: PRIOR, CONCOMITANT, ANTI-CANCER MEDICATION, or GENERAL CONMED.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further categorization of medications/ treatment. Examples: CHEMOTHERAPY, HORMONAL THERAPY, ALTERNATIVE THERAPY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMPRESP
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate whether (Y/null) information about the use of a specific medication was solicited on the CRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMOCCUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: When the use of specific medications is solicited, CMOCCUR is used to indicate whether or not (Y/N) use of the medication occurred. Values are null for medications not specifically solicited.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate that a question about a pre-specified medication was not answered. Should be null or have a value of NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes the reason concomitant medication was not collected. Used in conjunction with CMSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMINDC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Denotes why a medication was taken or administered. Examples: NAUSEA, HYPERTENSION.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMCLAS
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Drug class. May be obtained from coding. When coding to a single class, populate with class value. If using a dictionary and coding to multiple classes, then follow assumption 4.1.2.8.3 or omit CMCLAS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMCLASCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Class code corresponding to CMCLAS. Drug class. May be obtained from coding. When coding to a single class, populate with class code. If using a dictionary and coding to multiple classes, then follow assumption 4.1.2.8.3 or omit CMCLASCD.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Amount of CMTRT taken.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSTXT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Dosing amounts or a range of dosing information collected in text form. Units may be stored in CMDOSU. Example: 200-400, 15-20.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Units for CMDOSE, CMDOSTXT, and CMDOSTOT. Examples: ng, mg, or mg/kg.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSFRM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Dose form for CMTRT. Examples: TABLET, LOTION.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSFRQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of CMDOSE within a specific time period. Examples: BID (twice daily), Q12H (every 12 hours).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSTOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Total daily dose of CMTRT using the units in CMDOSU. Total dose over a period other than day could be recorded in a separate Supplemental Qualifier variable. CMDOSTOT should be used in addition to CMDOSE, and not in place of it.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDOSRGM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Text description of the (intended) schedule or regimen for the Intervention. Examples: TWO WEEKS ON, TWO WEEKS OFF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMROUTE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Route of administration for CMTRT. Examples: ORAL, INTRAVENOUS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSTDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of Start of Medication
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of start of medication relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMENDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of End of Medication
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of end of medication relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMDUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Collected duration for a treatment episode. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSTRF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes the start of the medication relative to sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). If information such as PRIOR, ONGOING, or CONTINUING was collected, this information may be translated into CMSTRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMENRF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes the end of the medication relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). If information such as PRIOR, ONGOING, or CONTINUING was collected, this information may be translated into CMENRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSTRTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Start Relative to Reference Time Point
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifies the start of the medication as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable CMSTTPT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMSTTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by CMSTRTPT. Examples: 2003-12-15 or VISIT 1.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMENRTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Description: End Relative to Reference Time Point
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifies the end of the medication as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable CMENTPT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CMENTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by CMENRTPT. Examples: 2003-12-25 or VISIT 2.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined identifier. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a CRF Page.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXTRT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the intervention treatment - usually the verbatim name of the investigational treatment given during the dosing period for the observation.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of related records. Example: COMPARATOR CLASS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further categorization of treatment.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Amount of EXTRT administered or given.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSTXT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Dosing amounts or a range of dosing information collected in text form. Example: 200-400.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Units for EXDOSE and EXDOSTOT. Examples: ng, mg, or mg/kg.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSFRM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Dose form for EXTRT. Examples: TABLET, LOTION.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSFRQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of EXDOSE within a specific time period. Examples: BID (twice daily), Q4S (once every four weeks), BIS (twice a week).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EXDOSTOT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Total daily dose of EXTRT using the units in EXDOSU. Total dose over a period other than day could be recorded in a separate Supplemental Qualifier variable.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RFXSTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: First date of exposure to any protocol-specified treatment or therapy, equal to the earliest value of EXSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RFXENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Last date of exposure to any protocol-specified treatment or therapy, equal to the latest value of EXENDTC (or the latest value of EXSTDTC if EXENDTC was not collected or is missing).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RFICDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of informed consent in ISO 8601 character format. This will be the same as the date of informed consent in the Disposition domain, if that protocol milestone is documented. Would be null only in studies not collecting the date of informed consent.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RFPENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time when subject ended participation or follow-up in a trial, as defined in the protocol, in ISO 8601 character format. Should correspond to the last known date of contact. Examples include completion date, withdrawal date, last follow-up, date recorded for lost to follow up, or death date.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DTHDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of death for any subject who died, in ISO 8601 format. Should represent the date/time that is captured in the clinical-trial database.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DTHFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicates the subject died. Should be Y or null. Should be populated even when the death date is unknown.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ACTARMCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Code of actual Arm. When an Arm is not planned (not in Trial Arms), ACTARMCD will be UNPLAN. Randomized subjects who were not treated will be given a value of NOTTRT. Values should be "SCRNFAIL" for screen failures and "NOTASSGN" for subjects not assigned to treatment. Restricted to values in Trial Arms in all other cases. ACTARMCD is limited to 20 characters and does not have special character restrictions. The maximum length of ACTARMCD is longer than for other short variables to accommodate the kind of values that are likely to be needed for crossover trials.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ACTARM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description of actual Arm. When an Arm is not planned (not in Trial Arms), ACTARM will be "Unplanned Treatment". Randomized subjects who were not treated will be given a value of "Not Treated". Values should be "Screen Failure" for screen failures and "Not Assigned" for subjects not assigned to treatment. Restricted to values in Trial Arms in all other cases.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SPDEVID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined identifier for the device

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product. This must be a unique number, and could be a compound identifier formed by concatenating STUDYID-SITEID-SUBJID.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Subject identifier, which must be unique within the study. Often the ID of the subject as recorded on a CRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RFSTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Reference Start Date/time for the subject in ISO 8601 character format. Usually equivalent to date/time when subject was first exposed to study treatment. Required for all randomized subjects; will be null for all subjects who did not meet the milestone the date requires, such as screen failures or unassigned subjects.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RFENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Reference End Date/time for the subject in ISO 8601 character format. Usually equivalent to the date/time when subject was determined to have ended the trial, and often equivalent to date/time of last exposure to study treatment. Required for all randomized subjects; null for screen failures or unassigned subjects.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RFXSTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: First date of exposure to any protocol-specified treatment or therapy, equal to the earliest value of EXSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RFXENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Last date of exposure to any protocol-specified treatment or therapy, equal to the latest value of EXENDTC (or the latest value of EXSTDTC if EXENDTC was not collected or is missing).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RFICDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of informed consent in ISO 8601 character format. This will be the same as the date of informed consent in the Disposition domain, if that protocol milestone is documented. Would be null only in studies not collecting the date of informed consent.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RFPENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time when subject ended participation or follow-up in a trial, as defined in the protocol, in ISO 8601 character format. Should correspond to the last known date of contact. Examples include completion date, withdrawal date, last follow-up, date recorded for lost to follow up, or death date.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DTHDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of death for any subject who died, in ISO 8601 format. Should represent the date/time that is captured in the clinical-trial database.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DTHFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicates the subject died. Should be Y or null. Should be populated even when the death date is unknown.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SITEID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a site within a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: INVID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: An identifier to describe the Investigator for the study. May be used in addition to SITEID. Not needed if SITEID is equivalent to INVID.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: INVNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the investigator for a site.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: BRTHDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of birth of the subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: AGE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Age expressed in AGEU. May be derived from RFSTDTC and BRTHDTC, but BRTHDTC may not be available in all cases (due to subject privacy concerns).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: AGEU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Units associated with AGE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SEX
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sex of the subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RACE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Race of the subject. Sponsors should refer to Collection of Race and Ethnicity Data in Clinical Trials (FDA, September 2005) for guidance regarding the collection of race (http://www.fda.gov/cder/guidance/5656fnl.htm) See Assumption below regarding RACE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ETHNIC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The ethnicity of the subject. Sponsors should refer to Collection of Race and Ethnicity Data in Clinical Trials (FDA, September 2005) for guidance regarding the collection of ethnicity (http://www.fda.gov/cder/guidance/5656fnl.htm).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ARMCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: ARMCD is limited to 20 characters and does not have special character restrictions. The maximum length of ARMCD is longer than for other short variables to accommodate the kind of values that are likely to be needed for crossover trials. For example, if ARMCD values for a seven-period crossover were constructed using two-character abbreviations for each treatment and separating hyphens, the length of ARMCD values would be 20.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ARM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the Arm to which the subject was assigned.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ACTARMCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Code of actual Arm. When an Arm is not planned (not in Trial Arms), ACTARMCD will be UNPLAN. Randomized subjects who were not treated will be given a value of NOTTRT. Values should be SCRNFAIL for screen failures and NOTASSGN for subjects not assigned to treatment. Restricted to values in Trial Arms in all other cases. ACTARMCD is limited to 20 characters and does not have special character restrictions. The maximum length of ACTARMCD is longer than for other short variables to accommodate the kind of values that are likely to be needed for crossover trials.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ACTARM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description of actual Arm. When an Arm is not planned (not in Trial Arms), ACTARM will be Unplanned Treatment. Randomized subjects who were not treated will be given a value of Not Treated. Values should be Screen Failure for screen failures and Not Assigned for subjects not assigned to treatment. Restricted to values in Trial Arms in all other cases.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: COUNTRY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Country of the investigational site in which the subject participated in the trial.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DMDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of demographic data collection.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DMDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of collection measured as integer days.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RDOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain of the parent record(s). Null for comments collected on a general comments or additional information CRF page.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: COSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IDVAR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifying variable in the parent dataset that identifies the record(s) to which the comment applies. Examples AESEQ or CMGRPID. Used only when individual comments are related to domain records. Null for comments collected on separate CRFs.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IDVARVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Value of identifying variable of the parent record(s). Used only when individual comments are related to domain records. Null for comments collected on separate CRFs.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: COREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference associated with the comment. May be the CRF page number (e.g. 650), or a module name (e.g. DEMOG), or a combination of information that identifies the reference (e.g. 650-VITALS-VISIT 2).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: COVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The text of the comment. Text over 200 characters can be added to additional columns COVAL1-COVALn. See assumption 5.2.1.1.3.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: COEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to describe the originator of the comment. Examples: CENTRAL, REVIEWER, ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CODTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of comment on dedicated comment form. Should be null if this is a child record of another domain or if comment date was not collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SESEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. Should be assigned to be consistent chronological order.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ETCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ELEMENT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 2. If an encountered Element differs from the planned Element to the point that it is considered a new Element, then use UNPLAN as the value for ETCD to represent this Element.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SESTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Start date/time for an Element for each subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SEENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: End date/time for an Element for each subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TAETORD

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Number that gives the planned order of the Element within the subject's assigned ARM.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EPOCH
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Epoch associated with the Element in the planned sequence of Elements for the ARM to which the subject was assigned

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SEUPDES
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description of what happened to the subject during this unplanned Element. Used only if ETCD has the value of UNPLAN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. (Decimal numbering may be useful for inserting unplanned visits.)2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY as a text description of the clinical encounter.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the start of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SVSTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Start date/time for a Visit.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SVENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: End date/time of a Visit.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SVSTDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of Start of Visit
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of start of visit relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SVENDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of End of Visit
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of end of visit relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SVUPDES
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description of what happened to the subject during an unplanned visit.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SPDEVID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined identifier for the device.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DISEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness within a parameter within a device (SPDEVID) within dataset

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DIPARMCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the identifier characteristic of the device.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DIPARM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the identifier characteristic of the device.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DIVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Value for the parameter.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RDOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain of the parent record(s). Null for comments collected on a general comments or additional information CRF page.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: COSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IDVAR
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifying variable in the parent dataset that identifies the record(s) to which the comment applies. Examples AESEQ or CMGRPID. Used only when individual comments are related to domain records. Null for comments collected on separate CRFs.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IDVARVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Value of identifying variable of the parent record(s). Used only when individual comments are related to domain records. Null for comments collected on separate CRFs.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: COREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference associated with the comment. May be the CRF page number (e.g. 650), or a module name (e.g. DEMOG), or a combination of information that identifies the reference (e.g. 650-VITALS-VISIT 2).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: COVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The text of the comment. Text over 200 characters can be added to additional columns COVAL1-COVALn. See assumption 5.2.1.1.3.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: COEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to describe the originator of the comment. Examples: CENTRAL, REVIEWER, ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: CODTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of comment on dedicated comment form. Should be null if this is a child record of another domain or if comment date was not collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IDVAR
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the identifying variable in the general-observation-class dataset that identifies the related record(s). Examples include --SEQ and --GRPID.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IDVARVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Value of identifying variable described in IDVAR. If --SEQ is the variable being used to describe this record, then the value of --SEQ would be entered here.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RELTYPE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifies the hierarchical level of the records in the relationship. Values should be either ONE or MANY. Used only when identifying a relationship between datasets (as described in Section 8.3).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RELID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique value within USUBJID that identifies the relationship. All records for the same USUBJID that have the same RELID are considered "related/associated." RELID can be any value the sponsor chooses, and is only meaningful within the RELREC dataset to identify the related/associated Domain records.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RDOMAIN

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique Subject Identifier of the Parent record(s).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IDVAR
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifying variable in the dataset that identifies the related record(s). Examples: --SEQ, --GRPID.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IDVARVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Value of identifying variable of the parent record(s).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The short name of the Qualifier variable, which is used as a column name in a domain view with data from the parent domain. The value in QNAM cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST"). QNAM cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. This will often be the column name in the sponsor‘s operational dataset.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QLABEL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: This is the long name or label associated with QNAM. The value in QLABEL cannot be longer than 40 characters. This will often be the column label in the sponsor‘s Original dataset.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of, response to, or value associated with QNAM. A value for this column is required; no records can be in SUPP-- with a null value for QVAL.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QORIG
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Since QVAL can represent a mixture of collected (on a CRF), derived, or assigned items, QORIG is used to indicate the origin of this data. Examples include CRF, ASSIGNED, or DERIVED. See Section 4.1.1.8.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: QEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Should be null for records that contain objectively collected or derived data. Some examples include ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, STATISTICIAN, DATABASE ADMINISTRATOR, CLINICAL COORDINATOR, etc.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. (Decimal numbering may be useful for inserting unplanned visits.) 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY as a text description of the clinical encounter.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the start of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SVSTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Start date/time for a Visit.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SVENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: End date/time of a Visit.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SVSTDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of Start of Visit
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of start of visit relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SVENDY
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Study Day of End of Visit
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Study day of end of visit relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SVUPDES
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description of what happened to the subject during an unplanned visit.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DIPARMCD

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DIPARM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the identifier characteristic of the device.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DUSTRESN

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DUSTRESU

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SESEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. Should be assigned to be consistent chronological order.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ETCD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name. 2. If an encountered Element differs from the planned Element to the point that it is considered a new Element, then use "UNPLAN" as the value for ETCD to represent this Element.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ELEMENT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The name of the Element. If ETCD has a value of "UNPLAN" then ELEMENT should be Null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SESTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Start date/time for an Element for each subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SEENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: End date/time for an Element for each subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TAETORD
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Order of Element within Arm
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Number that gives the planned order of the Element within the subject's assigned ARM.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EPOCH
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Epoch associated with the Element in the planned sequence of Elements for the ARM to which the subject was assigned

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SEUPDES
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Description of what happened to the subject during this unplanned Element. Used only if ETCD has the value of "UNPLAN".

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product. This must be a unique number, and could be a compound identifier formed by concatenating STUDYID-SITEID-SUBJID.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Subject identifier, which must be unique within the study. Often the ID of the subject as recorded on a CRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RFSTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Reference Start Date/time for the subject in ISO 8601 character format. Usually equivalent to date/time when subject was first exposed to study treatment. Required for all randomized subjects; will be null for all subjects who did not meet the milestone the date requires, such as screen failures or unassigned subjects.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RFENDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Reference End Date/time for the subject in ISO 8601 character format. Usually equivalent to the date/time when subject was determined to have ended the trial, and often equivalent to date/time of last exposure to study treatment. Required for all randomized subjects; null for screen failures or unassigned subjects.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SITEID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a site within a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: INVID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: An identifier to describe the Investigator for the study. May be used in addition to SITEID. Not needed if SITEID is equivalent to INVID.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: INVNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the investigator for a site.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: BRTHDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of birth of the subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: AGE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Age expressed in AGEU. May be derived from RFSTDTC and BRTHDTC, but BRTHDTC may not be available in all cases (due to subject privacy concerns).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: AGEU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Units associated with AGE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SEX
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sex of the subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: RACE
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Race of the subject. Sponsors should refer to "Collection of Race and Ethnicity Data in Clinical Trials" (FDA, September 2005) for guidance regarding the collection of race (http://www.fda.gov/cder/guidance/5656fnl.htm) See Assumption below regarding RACE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ETHNIC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The ethnicity of the subject. Sponsors should refer to "Collection of Race and Ethnicity Data in Clinical Trials" (FDA, September 2005) for guidance regarding the collection of ethnicity (http://www.fda.gov/cder/guidance/5656fnl.htm).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ARMCD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: ARMCD is limited to 20 characters and does not have special character restrictions. The maximum length of ARMCD is longer than for other "short" variables to accommodate the kind of values that are likely to be needed for crossover trials. For example, if ARMCD values for a seven-period crossover were constructed using two-character abbreviations for each treatment and separating hyphens, the length of ARMCD values would be 20.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ARM
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the Arm to which the subject was assigned.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: COUNTRY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Country of the investigational site in which the subject participated in the trial.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DMDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of demographic data collection.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DMDY

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ETCD

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ELEMENT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The name of the Element. The same Element may occur more than once within an Arm.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TABRANCH
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Condition subject met, at a "branch" in the trial design at the end of this Element, to be included in this Arm; (e.g., randomization to DRUG X).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TATRANS
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: If the trial design allows a subject to transition to an Element other than the next Element in sequence, then the conditions for transitioning to those other Elements, and the alternative Element sequences, are specified in this rule (e.g., Responders go to washout).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EPOCH
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the Trial Epoch with which this Element of the Arm is associated.

ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The name of the Element.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TESTRL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Expresses rule for beginning Element.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TEENRL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Expresses rule for ending Element. Either TEENRL or TEDUR must be present for each Element.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TEDUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned Duration of Element in ISO 8601 format. Used when the rule for ending the Element is applied after a fixed duration.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IETESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name IETEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in IETESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST"). IETESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. The prefix "IE" is used to ensure consistency with the IE domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IETEST
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Full text of the inclusion or exclusion criterion. The prefix "IE" is used to ensure consistency with the IE domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IECAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for Categorization of the inclusion or exclusion criteria.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IESCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further Categorization of the exception criterion. Can be used to distinguish criteria for a sub-study or for to categorize as a major or minor exceptions. Examples: MAJOR, MINOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TIRL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Rule that expresses the criterion in computer-executable form (see assumption 4 below).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TIVERS
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The number of this version of the Inclusion/Exclusion criteria. May be omitted if there is only one version.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain, which must be TS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness within a dataset. Allows inclusion of multiple records for the same TSPARMCD, and can be used to join related records.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a group of related records

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSPARMCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: TSPARMCD (the companion to TSPARM) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that TSPARMCD will need to serve as variable names. Examples: AGEMIN, AGEMAX

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSPARM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Term for the Trial Summary Parameter. The value in TSPARM cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples Planned Minimum Age of Subjects, Planned Maximum Age of Subjects

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Value of TSPARM. Example: "ASTHMA" when TSPARM value is "Trial Indication". TSVAL can only be null when TSVALNF is populated. Text over 200 characters can be added to additional columns TSVAL1-TSVALn.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the DOMAIN

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY as a text description of the clinical encounter.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Planned study day of VISIT. 2. Due to its sequential nature, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ARMCD
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1.ARMCD is limited to 20 characters and does not have special character restrictions. The maximum length of ARMCD is longer than for other "short" variables to accommodate the kind of values that are likely to be needed for crossover trials. For example, if ARMCD values for a seven-period crossover were constructed using two-character abbreviations for each treatment and separating hyphens, the length of ARMCD values would be 20. 2. If the timing of Visits for a trial does not depend on which ARM a subject is in, then ARMCD should be null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ARM
ProSDTMVariable.Format: Variable may be subject to controlled terminology.
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Name given to an Arm or Treatment Group. 2. If the timing of Visits for a trial does not depend on which Arm a subject is in, then Arm should be left blank.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TVSTRL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Rule describing when the Visit starts, in relation to the sequence of Elements.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TVENRL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Rule describing when the Visit ends, in relation to the sequence of Elements.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSVALNF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Null flavor for the value of TSPARM, to be populated if and only if TSVAL is null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSVALCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: This is the code of the term in TSVAL. For example; 6CW7F3G59X is the code for Gabapentin, C49488 is the code for Y. The length of this variable can be longer than 8 to accommodate the length of the external terminology.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSVCDREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The name of the Reference Terminology from which TSVALCD is taken. For example; CDISC, SNOMED, ISO 8601.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSVCDVER
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The version number of the Reference Terminology, if applicable.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ARMCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: ARMCD is limited to 20 characters and does not have special character restrictions. The maximum length of ARMCD is longer than that for other short variables to accommodate the kind of values that are likely to be needed for crossover trials. For example, if ARMCD values for a seven-period crossover were constructed using two-character abbreviations for each treatment and separating hyphens, the length of ARMCD values would be 20.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ARM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name given to an Arm or treatment group.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TAETORD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Number that gives the order of the Element within the Arm.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ETCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ELEMENT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The name of the Element. The same Element may occur more than once within an Arm.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TABRANCH
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Condition subject met, at a branch in the trial design at the end of this Element, to be included in this Arm; (e.g., randomization to DRUG X).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TATRANS
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: If the trial design allows a subject to transition to an Element other than the next Element in sequence, then the conditions for transitioning to those other Elements, and the alternative Element sequences, are specified in this rule (e.g., Responders go to washout).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: EPOCH
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the Trial Epoch with which this Element of the Arm is associated.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ETCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ELEMENT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The name of the Element.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TESTRL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Expresses rule for beginning Element.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TEENRL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Expresses rule for ending Element. Either TEENRL or TEDUR must be present for each Element.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TEDUR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned Duration of Element in ISO 8601 format. Used when the rule for ending the Element is applied after a fixed duration.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY as a text description of the clinical encounter.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Planned study day of VISIT. 2. Due to its sequential nature, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ARMCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1.ARMCD is limited to 20 characters and does not have special character restrictions. The maximum length of ARMCD is longer than for other short variables to accommodate the kind of values that are likely to be needed for crossover trials. For example, if ARMCD values for a seven-period crossover were constructed using two-character abbreviations for each treatment and separating hyphens, the length of ARMCD values would be 20. 2. If the timing of Visits for a trial does not depend on which ARM a subject is in, then ARMCD should be null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: ARM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Name given to an Arm or Treatment Group. 2. If the timing of Visits for a trial does not depend on which Arm a subject is in, then Arm should be left blank.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TVSTRL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Rule describing when the Visit starts, in relation to the sequence of Elements.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TVENRL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Rule describing when the Visit ends, in relation to the sequence of Elements.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TDORDER
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A number given to ensure ordinal sequencing of the planned assessment schedules within a trial.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TDANCVAR
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A reference to the date variable name that provides the start point from which the planned disease assessment schedule is measured. This must be a referenced from the ADaM ADSL dataset e.g. ANCH1DT. Note: TDANCVAR will contain the name of a reference date variable.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TDSTOFF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A fixed offset from the date provided by the variable referenced in TDANCVAR. This is used when the timing of planned cycles does not start on the exact day referenced in the variable indicated in TDANCVAR. The value of this variable will be either zero or a positive value and will be represented in ISO 8601 character format.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TDTGTPAI
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The planned interval between disease assessments represented in ISO 8601 character format.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TDMINPAI
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The lower limit of the allowed range for the planned interval between disease assessments represented in ISO 8601 character format.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TDMAXPAI
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The upper limit of the allowed range for the planned interval between disease assessments represented in ISO 8601 character format.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TDNUMRPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: This variable must represent the maximum number of actual assessments for the analysis that this disease assessment schedule describes. In a trial where the maximum number of assessments is not defined explicitly in the protocol (e.g. assessments occur until death) TDNUMRPT should represent the maximum number of disease assessments that support the efficacy analysis, encountered by any subject across the trial at that point in time.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IETESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name IETEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in IETESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., 1TEST). IETESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. The prefix IE is used to ensure consistency with the IE domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IETEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Full text of the inclusion or exclusion criterion. The prefix IE is used to ensure consistency with the IE domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IECAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for categorization of the inclusion or exclusion criteria.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: IESCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further categorization of the exception criterion. Can be used to distinguish criteria for a sub-study or for to categorize as a major or minor exceptions. Examples: MAJOR, MINOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TIRL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Rule that expresses the criterion in computer-executable form (see assumption 4 below).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TIVERS
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The number of this version of the Inclusion/Exclusion criteria. May be omitted if there is only one version.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique identifier for a study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain, which must be TS.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness within a dataset. Allows inclusion of multiple records for the same TSPARMCD, and can be used to join related records.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a group of related records

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSPARMCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: TSPARMCD (the companion to TSPARM) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that TSPARMCD will need to serve as variable names. Examples: AGEMIN, AGEMAX

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSPARM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Term for the Trial Summary Parameter. The value in TSPARM cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples Planned Minimum Age of Subjects, Planned Maximum Age of Subjects

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Value of TSPARM. Example: ASTHMA when TSPARM value is Trial Indication. TSVAL can only be null when TSVALNF is populated. Text over 200 characters can be added to additional columns TSVAL1-TSVALn.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSVALNF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Null flavor for the value of TSPARM, to be populated if and only if TSVAL is null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSVALCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: This is the code of the term in TSVAL. For example; 6CW7F3G59X is the code for Gabapentin, C49488 is the code for Y. The length of this variable can be longer than 8 to accommodate the length of the external terminology.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSVCDREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The name of the Reference Terminology from which TSVALCD is taken. For example; CDISC, SNOMED, ISO 8601.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: TSVCDVER
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: The version number of the Reference Terminology, if applicable.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FAGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a CRF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FATESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in FATEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in FATESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g. 1TEST). FATESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Example: SEV, OCCUR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FATEST
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in FATEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Severity/Intensity, Occurrence

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FAOBJ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to describe the object or focal point of the findings observation that is represented by --TEST. Examples: the term (such as Acne) describing a clinical sign or symptom that is being measured by a Severity test, or an event such as VOMIT where the volume of Vomit is being measured by a VOLUME test.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FACAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of related records. Examples: GERD, PRE-SPECIFIED AE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further categorization of FACAT.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FAORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Result or Finding in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Result of the test as originally received or collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FAORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for FAORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from FAORRES in a standard format or standard units. FASTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in FASTRESN. For example, if a test has results NONE, NEG, and NEGATIVE in FAORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning; they could be represented in standard format in FASTRESC as NEGATIVE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from FASTRESC. FASTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized unit used for FASTRESC and FASTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FASTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate that the measurement was not done. Should be null if a result exists in FAORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FAREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a question was not answered. Example: subject refused. Used in conjunction with FASTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FALOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to specify the location of the clinical evaluation. Example: LEFT ARM

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FABLFL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be Y or null.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FAEVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Should be null for records that contain collected or derived data. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, VENDOR.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: FADY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Study day of collection, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics. This formula should be consistent across the submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: STUDYID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Unique Identifier for a Study.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: DOMAIN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: USUBJID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across submission.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRSEQ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRGRPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRREFID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Internal or external specimen identifier. Example: Specimen ID.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRSPID
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Sponsor defined identifier.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRTESTCD
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Skin Response Test or Exam Short Name
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in SRTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in SRTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number. SRTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRTEST
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Skin Response Test or Examination Name
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in SRTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. (E.g., Wheal Diameter).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SROBJ
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to describe the object or focal point of the findings observation that is represented by --TEST. Examples: the dose of the immunogenic material or the allergen associated with the response. (e.g., Johnson Grass IgE 0.15 BAU mL).

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to define a category of Topic-variable values across subjects.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRSCAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: A further categorization of SRCAT values.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRORRES
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Results or Findings in Original Units
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Results of measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRORRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for SRORRES. Example: mm.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRSTRESC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from SRORRES in a standard format or in standard units. SRSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in SRSTRESN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRSTRESN
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from SRSTRESC. SRSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRSTRESU
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Standardized units used for SRSTRESC and SRSTRESN, Example: mm.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRSTAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Used to indicate exam not done. Should be null if a result exists in SRORRES.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRREASND
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Describes why a measurement or test was not performed. Used in conjunction with SRSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRNAM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor who provided the test results

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRSPEC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Defines the types of specimen used for a measurement. E.g., SKIN.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRLOC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Location relevant to the collection of the measurement.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRLAT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing laterality of intervention administration. Examples: RIGHT, LEFT, BILATERAL

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRMETHOD
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Method of test or examination (ELISA, EIA Microneutralization, PRNT (Plaque Reduction Neutralization Tests)

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SREVAL
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Role of person who provided evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Should be null for records that contain collected or derived data. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, VENDOR

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISIT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: VISITDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Collection date and time of an observation represented in ISO 8601

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRDY
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Actual study day of visit/collection/exam expressed in integer days relative to sponsor- defined RFSTDTC in Demographics

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRTPT
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: 1. Text Description of time when measurement should be taken. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See SRTPTNUM and SRTPTREF. Examples: Start, 5 min post.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRTPTNUM
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Numerical version of SRTPT to aid in sorting.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRELTM
ProSDTMVariable.Description: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a fixed time point reference (SRTPTREF). Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration. Examples: -PT15M to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by EGTPTREF, or PT8H to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by SRTPTREF.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRTPTREF
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by SRELTM, SRTPTNUM, and SRTPT. Example: INTRADERMAL INJECTION.

ProSDTMVariable.Caption: SRRFTDTC
ProSDTMVariable.Notes: Date/time of the reference time point, SRTPTREF.
